  const INSIGHTS            = {
  "Q1": "<p>The <strong>41% 'Others' category</strong> (16,497 posts) signals significant noise in the community. Sample posts show off-topic content (TikTok/Instagram advice, general life comments like 'Ngon đấy'). This suggests the community serves as a general Vietnamese networking space rather than a focused seller hub. <strong>Recommendation: Implement stricter moderation or create topic-specific channels to improve signal-to-noise ratio.</strong></p>",
  "Q2": "<p>Amazon sellers show strong concentration in <strong>MT1 (2,357)</strong> and <strong>MT4 (2,049)</strong>, totaling 4,406 mentions. Sample posts reveal sellers actively discussing <strong>FBA/FBM fulfillment strategies</strong>, warehouse logistics, and operational best practices (e.g., 'kho canada bên e đầy đủ dịch vụ FBA-FBM'). This indicates Amazon sellers prioritize supply-chain and fulfillment discussions over other topics, suggesting these are pain points requiring peer guidance.</p>",
  "Q3": "<p>Sellers report <strong>account suspension (6.8%)</strong> and <strong>account issues (6.78%)</strong> at 5× the rate of prospects (1.65% and 1.67% respectively). Combined, account health concerns represent <strong>18.7% of seller discourse</strong> versus only <strong>5.8% for prospects</strong>. This 12.9-point gap reflects a critical pain point: established sellers face ongoing compliance, verification, and suspension risks that new entrants have not yet encountered. Samples show sellers actively seeking fulfillment support and case management, indicating reactive problem-solving rather than proactive planning.</p>",
  "Q4": "<p>A dramatic <strong>+70% spike on Mar 16</strong> (Week 12) marks the peak of a three-week surge (Mar 9–23). Sample posts reveal this period coincides with <strong>heavy promotion of Amazon FBA/FBM fulfillment services</strong>, particularly from Canada warehouse operators and US item resellers. Posts like \"kho canada bên e đầy đủ dịch vụ FBA-FBM\" and \"Nhận đơn Amazon US item từ 40-150\" indicate sellers actively recruiting and cross-promoting logistics solutions, driving community discussion and engagement spikes.</p>",
  "Q5": "<p>Account suspension complaints (1,067 mentions) represent the second-largest negative category, with Friday (1,504 total negative mentions) showing the highest weekly concentration. The 9 AM–1 PM window captures 2,724 complaints (27.7% of all negative posts), with hour 11 alone accounting for 755 mentions. Sample posts reveal sellers facing sudden account locks and 30-day freezes without clear resolution pathways: <em>\"tài khoản mới ai cũng bị dính thôi, thường là giam 30 ngày\"</em> (new accounts all get hit, usually locked for 30 days). This timing suggests sellers check account status after overnight operations, discovering suspensions and flooding the community for support.</p>",
  "Q6": "<p>Negative discussions intensify when sellers are offline or during late evening hours, when <strong>account restrictions and 30-day lockdowns</strong> are the dominant complaint topic. Users report being unable to contact support effectively, leading to <strong>community-driven misinformation</strong> (e.g., 'it will auto-release after 30 days'). This creates a vacuum where <strong>peer advice replaces official guidance</strong>, amplifying frustration and eroding trust in the platform.</p>",
  "Q7": "<p>With <strong>1,517 mentions of 'Success & Income'</strong> dominating the benefit conversation, sellers are primarily motivated by profit potential. However, samples reveal a critical gap: while sellers chase high-margin niches (e.g., 'Ceramic Flower Vase,' 'Pet niche at $150B'), many lack <strong>financial modeling and P&L clarity</strong>. One post explicitly warns about 'falling into the cashflow trap'—indicating that Amazon's earning potential attracts sellers who then struggle with operational execution. The narrative is aspirational, but the reality check is harsh.</p>",
  "Q8": "<p>Account lockdowns (16 mentions) and scam concerns (15 mentions) represent <strong>31 of 76 total churn triggers</strong>—nearly 41% of documented reasons sellers leave. Sample posts reveal sellers facing sudden account suspensions after brand registration or policy verification failures, with minimal recourse. One seller reports: \"em mới lập tài khoản, sau khi add brand vào thì bị khóa\" (newly registered, locked after adding brand). This suggests policy enforcement is aggressive and poorly communicated, creating distrust among both new and established sellers.</p>",
  "Q9": "<p>Sellers comprise <strong>57.8% of join discussions</strong> (1,591 mentions), indicating strong seller interest in community participation. However, <strong>Amazon sellers represent only 19.2% of join discussions</strong> (528 of 2,751), while non-Amazon sellers dominate at 38.6% (1,063). This gap widens dramatically in leave discussions, where <strong>Amazon sellers drop to 18.6% (113 of 608)</strong> while non-Amazon sellers remain at 74.5% (453). The samples reveal sellers actively recruiting peers (\"kho canada bên e đầy đủ dịch vụ FBA-FBM\") and discussing platform trade-offs, suggesting Amazon's ecosystem may face retention challenges compared to alternative platforms.</p>",
  "Q10": "<p><strong>Apparel & Fashion leads with 448 mentions</strong>, significantly outpacing all other categories. This reflects strong consumer demand and seller interest in clothing, footwear, and fashion accessories. The category's dominance suggests it remains the most accessible entry point for Vietnamese sellers on Amazon, with established supply chains and lower barriers to entry compared to regulated categories.</p>",
  "Q11": "<p><strong>System errors dominate 47% of all issue mentions (122/177)</strong>, with FBA (13 issues) and FBM (12 issues) bearing the brunt. This suggests critical platform stability problems that directly undermine seller confidence. When sellers cannot reliably track inventory, process orders, or access dashboards, operational chaos follows. The gap between FBA's high usage (119) and low satisfaction (17/119 = 14%) reveals sellers are <strong>forced to use FBA despite frustration</strong>, not because they trust it.</p>",
  "Q12": "<p>With <strong>258 mentions and only 33% satisfaction</strong>, accounting and tax services represent the most critical unmet need in the SOA seller community. Despite 23 sellers explicitly flagging urgent needs, the low satisfaction score suggests existing third-party providers are either unavailable, unaffordable, or inadequate for Vietnamese sellers' compliance requirements. This is likely driven by complex Vietnamese tax regulations, cross-border VAT complexity, and the need for Amazon-specific accounting expertise.</p>",
  "Q13": "<p><strong>General training courses lead with 35 mentions and 20 positive sentiments</strong>, yet sellers struggle to identify where to start. Posts reveal a critical gap: newcomers ask \"em nên bắt đầu từ đâu\" (where should I begin?) and \"có trung tâm hay đơn vị nào nhận đào tạo không\" (which training centers exist?), indicating <strong>poor discoverability of structured programs</strong>. The community lacks clarity on curriculum scope, duration, and ROI—sellers are uncertain whether to invest 1–200 million VND in courses when success stories remain anecdotal.</p>",
  "Q14": "<p>Despite 123 mentions, <strong>team building sentiment is paradoxical</strong>: 54% positive but 55% mixed/negative combined. Samples reveal the core tension—sellers celebrate team wins (\"Chia sẻ truyền cảm hứng quá\") but simultaneously struggle with <strong>support quality and hiring friction</strong>. One seller explicitly states: \"Support ko làm được gì luôn\" and \"Call tiếng Anh...team tiếng Anh cũng không chịu nhận.\" This suggests <strong>team scaling is aspirational, not operational</strong>. Sellers want to build but face retention, language barriers, and KPI misalignment (\"Cty mà cắn xén tiền kpi của nhân viên\").</p>"
};
